import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    group_counts = data['group'].value_counts()
    ax = group_counts.plot(kind='bar', color=['blue', 'green', 'orange'])
    plt.title('What is the distribution of groups in the dataset?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Group')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    ax.legend(group_counts.index, title='Groups', loc='upper right')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    # Group by 'group' and count the number of people in each group
    group_counts = data.groupby('group')['person'].count()

    # Create a stacked bar chart
    ax = group_counts.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True)

    # Set the title and labels
    plt.title('What is the distribution of people in each group?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Group')
    plt.ylabel('Number of People')

    # Add a legend
    ax.legend(['People Count'])

    # Rotate x-axis labels if needed
    plt.xticks(rotation=0)

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    most_common_group = data.groupby('person')['group'].agg(lambda x: x.value_counts().index[0]).reset_index()
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    sns.barplot(x='person', y='group', data=most_common_group, ax=ax, palette='viridis')
    ax.set_title('What is the most common group for each person?')
    ax.set_ylabel('Most Common Group')
    ax.set_xlabel('Person')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(title='Group', loc='upper right', labels=most_common_group['group'].unique())
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    scatter = ax.scatter(data['group'], data['person'], c=data['group'], cmap='viridis')
    legend1 = ax.legend(*scatter.legend_elements(), title="Groups")
    ax.add_artist(legend1)
    plt.title('What is the relationship between group and person?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Group')
    plt.ylabel('Person')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    # Count unique people in each group
    unique_people_counts = data.groupby('group')['person'].nunique()

    # Create a bar chart
    ax = unique_people_counts.plot(kind='bar', color=['blue', 'green', 'red'])
    plt.title('What is the distribution of unique people in each group?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Group')
    plt.ylabel('Unique People Count')

    # Add legend
    ax.legend(["Group 1", "Group 2", "Group 3"])

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
